{"title_page": "Alexandrea Owens", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress who played a cameo in Titanic}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Alexandrea Owens\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Alexandrea Kathryn Owens-Sarno\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1988|11|09}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Diego]], California, US\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = Alexandrea Owens\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 1997; 2014\u2013present\n| known_for          = Cora Cartmell in ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n'''Alexandrea Kathryn Owens''' (born November 9, 1988), also known as '''Alexandrea Owens-Sarno''', is an American actress. She is best known for her role as eight-year-old Cora Cartmell, a young steerage passenger in the 1997 film ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' who dances with Jack Dawson ([[Leonardo DiCaprio]]) at an Irish party.<ref name=uni/>\n\n==Biography==\n{{Quote box\n |width=225px\n |align=right\n |quoted=true\n |bgcolor= \n |salign=right\n |quote=You're still my best girl, Cora.\n|source=\u2013Jack Dawson to Cora Cartmell after switching partners to dance with Rose<ref name=vanity>{{cite web |url= https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/12/titanic-20th-anniversary-trudy-fabrizio-cora-tommy-irish-mom |title= Five Unforgettable Passengers Remember Life Aboard ''Titanic''|first=Donald|last=Liebenson|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=October 15, 2019|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]}}</ref>\n}}\nAlexandrea Kathryn Owens was born in 1988 in [[San Diego]], California.<ref name=cosmo/>\n\nShe made her acting debut as Cora Cartmell in [[James Cameron]]'s 1997 epic ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''. Her mother took both her and her younger sister Rachel, then 3, to audition for roles at the film set in [[Rosarito Beach]], [[Baja California]].<ref name=vanity/><ref name=uni>{{cite web |url= https://www.unilad.co.uk/featured/cora-from-titanic-reveals-how-much-she-still-makes-from-the-movie/ |title= Cora From Titanic Reveals Amazing Story About Leonardo DiCaprio On Set |first=Francesca|last=Donovan|date=December 19, 2018|accessdate=October 15, 2019|work=[[UNILAD]]}}</ref> Owens, then in third grade,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/keelyflaherty/heres-what-the-little-girl-from-titanic-looks-like-now#.iigYW8YLoL|title= Here's What The Little Girl From \"Titanic\" Looks Like Now|first=Keely|last=Flaherty|date=August 3, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2019|work=[[BuzzFeed]]}}</ref> lined up with ten other girls, all blondes, said a few lines and danced a few steps with the casting director, and was dismissed. A week later she was offered the role of Cora; her mother and sister were cast as extras.<ref name=uni/> The family spent six months on location during the filming.<ref name=uni/>\n\nShe became known as \"the ''Titanic'' girl\" among her schoolmates,<ref name=cosmo/> and has since been asked many times what it was like to perform opposite [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], then a teenage heartthrob,<ref name=uni/> who played the lead role of Jack Dawson. She recalls that he was very \"sweet\" to her, getting her peanut butter and jelly sandwiches, making faces at her from behind the camera, and chatting with her between takes.<ref name=uni/><ref name=cosmo/><ref name=buzz>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/keelyflaherty/leonardo-dicaprio-was-officially-the-sweetest-on-the-set-of#.ds1yzoaq |title=Leonardo DiCaprio Was Officially The Sweetest On The Set Of \"Titanic\"|first=Keely|last=Flaherty|date=August 4, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2019|work=BuzzFeed}}</ref> He also romped around and played tickling games with her younger sister.<ref name=vanity/>\n\nFollowing her appearance in ''Titanic'', Owens hired an agent and began auditioning for other film roles. She was constantly recognized on the street and asked for autographs, and finally decided to take a break from acting.<ref name=cosmo>{{cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/movies/news/a44416/titanic-cora-alexandrea-owens-leo-dreamboat/|title= The Little Girl From Titanic Has Dreamboat Leo Stories That Will Make You Melt|first=Alex|last=Rees|date=August 6, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2019|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]}}</ref> However, she has dutifully kept up with fan mail over the years and sends out autographed pictures of herself in her ''Titanic'' role.<ref name=uni/> After college she moved to [[Los Angeles]] and enrolled in acting classes.<ref name=uni/><ref name=cosmo/> She presently works in [[Improvisational theatre|improv]] and [[sketch comedy]].<ref name=vanity/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0654302}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owens, Alexandrea}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from San Diego]]\n[[Category:20th-century American people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American people]]\n[[Category:American women comedians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress who played a cameo in Titanic}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Alexandrea Owens\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Alexandrea Kathryn Owens\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1988|11|09}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Diego]], California, US\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   =\n| other_names   = Alexandrea Owens-Sarno\n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 1997; 2014\u2013present\n| known_for     = Cora Cartmell in ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''\n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Alexandrea Kathryn Owens''' (born November 9, 1988), also known as '''Alexandrea Owens-Sarno''', is an American actress. She is best known for her role as eight-year-old Cora Cartmell, a young steerage passenger in the 1997 film ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' who dances with Jack Dawson ([[Leonardo DiCaprio]]) at an Irish party.<ref name=uni/>\n\n==Biography==\n{{Quote box\n |width=225px\n |align=right\n |quoted=true\n |bgcolor= \n |salign=right\n |quote=You're still my best girl, Cora.\n|source=\u2013Jack Dawson to Cora Cartmell after switching partners to dance with Rose<ref name=vanity>{{cite web |url= https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/12/titanic-20th-anniversary-trudy-fabrizio-cora-tommy-irish-mom |title= Five Unforgettable Passengers Remember Life Aboard ''Titanic''|first=Donald|last=Liebenson|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=October 15, 2019|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]}}</ref>\n}}\nAlexandrea Kathryn Owens was born in 1988 in [[San Diego]], California.<ref name=cosmo/>\n\nShe made her acting debut as Cora Cartmell in [[James Cameron]]'s 1997 epic ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''. Her mother took both her and her younger sister Rachel, then 3, to audition for roles at the film set in [[Rosarito Beach]], [[Baja California]].<ref name=vanity/><ref name=uni>{{cite web |url= https://www.unilad.co.uk/featured/cora-from-titanic-reveals-how-much-she-still-makes-from-the-movie/ |title= Cora From Titanic Reveals Amazing Story About Leonardo DiCaprio On Set |first=Francesca|last=Donovan|date=December 19, 2018|accessdate=October 15, 2019|work=[[UNILAD]]}}</ref> Owens, then in third grade,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/keelyflaherty/heres-what-the-little-girl-from-titanic-looks-like-now#.iigYW8YLoL|title= Here's What The Little Girl From \"Titanic\" Looks Like Now|first=Keely|last=Flaherty|date=August 3, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2019|work=[[BuzzFeed]]}}</ref> lined up with ten other girls, all blondes, said a few lines and danced a few steps with the casting director, and was dismissed. A week later she was offered the role of Cora; her mother and sister were cast as extras.<ref name=uni/> The family spent six months on location during the filming.<ref name=uni/>\n\nShe became known as \"the ''Titanic'' girl\" among her schoolmates,<ref name=cosmo/> and has since been asked many times what it was like to perform opposite [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], then a teenage heartthrob,<ref name=uni/> who played the lead role of Jack Dawson. She recalls that he was very \"sweet\" to her, getting her peanut butter and jelly sandwiches, making faces at her from behind the camera, and chatting with her between takes.<ref name=uni/><ref name=cosmo/><ref name=buzz>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/keelyflaherty/leonardo-dicaprio-was-officially-the-sweetest-on-the-set-of#.ds1yzoaq |title=Leonardo DiCaprio Was Officially The Sweetest On The Set Of \"Titanic\"|first=Keely|last=Flaherty|date=August 4, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2019|work=BuzzFeed}}</ref> He also romped around and played tickling games with her younger sister.<ref name=vanity/>\n\nFollowing her appearance in ''Titanic'', Owens hired an agent and began auditioning for other film roles. She was constantly recognized on the street and asked for autographs, and finally decided to take a break from acting.<ref name=cosmo>{{cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/movies/news/a44416/titanic-cora-alexandrea-owens-leo-dreamboat/|title= The Little Girl From Titanic Has Dreamboat Leo Stories That Will Make You Melt|first=Alex|last=Rees|date=August 6, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2019|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]}}</ref> However, she has dutifully kept up with fan mail over the years and sends out autographed pictures of herself in her ''Titanic'' role.<ref name=uni/> After college she moved to [[Los Angeles]] and enrolled in acting classes.<ref name=uni/><ref name=cosmo/> She presently works in [[Improvisational theatre|improv]] and [[sketch comedy]].<ref name=vanity/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0654302}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owens, Alexandrea}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from San Diego]]\n[[Category:20th-century American people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American people]]\n[[Category:American women comedians]]\n", "name_user": "Adissonantmelody", "label": "safe", "comment": "Her birth name was incorrect", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandrea_Owens"}
{"title_page": "Mikhail Sumarokov-Elston", "text_new": "{{short description|Russian tennis player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name                  = Mikhail Sumarokov-Elston\n| image                 = Mikhail Sumarokov-Elston.jpg\n| fullname              = Mikhail Nikolayevich Sumarokov-Elston\n| country               = Russia\n| caption               = Mikhail Sumarokov-Elston partnering [[Paul Aym\u00e9]] in the doubles at the [[World Hard Court Championships]] in 1913\n| birth_date            = 1893\u20131894{{ref label|birth|a|a}}\n| birth_place           = [[Yalta]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date            = {{death date|1970|7|3|df=yes}}\n| death_place           = London, England\n| turnedpro             = 1906 <small>(amateur tour)</small><ref name=\"rusart\" /><br>1936 <small>(pro tour)</small><ref name=\"rusart\" />\n| retired               =\n| plays                 = right-handed (- 1905)<br>left-handed (1905 -)<ref name=\"rusart\" />\n| singlestitles         = 39<ref name=\"rusart\" />\n| WHCCresult             = 2R (1913)<ref name=\"rusart\" />\n| Olympicsresult         = 4R (1912)\n| OthertournamentsDoubles   = yes\n| WHCCDoublesresult         = 1R (1913){{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=60}}\n| OlympicsDoublesresult     = QF (1912)\n}}\n\n'''Mikhail Nikolayevich Sumarokov-Elston''' ({{lang-rus|\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0421\u0443\u043c\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0432-\u042d\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043d|p=m\u02b2\u026ax\u0250\u02c8il n\u02b2\u026ak\u0250\u02c8la\u026av\u02b2\u026at\u0255 s\u028am\u0250\u02c8rok\u0259f \u02c8el\u02b2st\u0259n}} {{lang-fr|link=no|Michel de Soumarokoff-Elston}};<ref name=\"PetitNi\u00e7ois\" /><ref name=\"figaro\" /> 1893 or 1894{{ref label|birth|a|a}}{{spaced ndash}}3 July 1970) was a Russian [[tennis]] player. He competed in two events at the [[1912 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\" /> Apart from his supremacy in the Russian national championships he was a Maltese champion and various French Riviera titleholder.<ref name=\"rusart\" />\n\n==Early life and family==\n[[File:Romanoffs leaving crimea.jpg|left|thumb|200px|The Sumarokovs along with the [[House of Romanov|Russian Imperial Family]] (latter pictured) leaving [[Crimea]]]]\nMikhail Sumarokov-Elston was born on in 1893{{ref label|birth|a|a}} to Count [[Nicholai Felixovich Sumarokov-Elston]] reserve Lieutenant of the [[1st Guard Cavalry division (Russian Empire)|Cavalry Regiment]] and Countess [[Sofia Mikhaylovna Koskul]].{{sfn|Fomenko|2004a|p=14}} He was the great-great-great-great-grandson of poet [[Alexander Sumarokov]] and the Great Great Grandson of [[Field Marshal]] [[Mikhail Kutuzov]].<ref name=\"yusupov\" />{{ref label|ancestor|b|b}} He was the nephew of tennis player Count [[Pavel Sumarokov-Elston]], who was his first coach and doubles partner, grandson of Count-General [[Felix Sumarokov-Elston]], Governor of [[Kuban Oblast]], and cousin of the infamous Prince [[Felix Yussupov]], who later became known as one of the collaborators who conspired to kill [[Grigori Rasputin]], cult leader and mentor of Empress consort of Russia [[Alexandra Feodorovna (Alix of Hesse)|Alexandra]].<ref name=\"rusart\" /><ref name=\"yusupov\" /> Felix provided his own palace for the murder spot and also shot Rasputin once before murdering him with the help of his accomplices.<ref name=\"Rasputin\" /> Mikhail had a sister called Elena and a brother Nicholas. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004a|p=17}} At the age of twelve he had a surgery on his right hand, which as a result was rendered unsuitable for tennis and he later switched to left-hand play.<ref name=\"rusart\" /> First he moved to [[Dresden]] and was trained by [[Kurt Bergmann]] and [[George K. Logie]].<ref name=\"rusart\" /> In 1906 he entered the second-class tournament of the [[Bad Homburg]] Championships, where he defeated [[Jack Hillyard]] amongst many to claim his first title.<ref name=\"rusart\" /><ref name=\"Straits\" /> With this he set a record of being the youngest winner ever at the time in the history of the tournament.<ref name=\"Straits\" /> In 1908 his father and brother died within two weeks of each other. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004a|p=19}} He moved back to his homeland and graduated first at the [[Annenschule]]{{sfn|Fomenko|2004a|p=21}} then at the Law Faculty of the [[Saint Petersburg State University|St. Petersburg University]].{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=75}}\n\nHe volunteered for the Russian [[Red Cross]] motorized ambulance unit at the outbreak of [[World War I]],{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=86}} and was assigned to the [[Black Sea Fleet]].{{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=87}} Her mother died on 3 April 1915.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=89}} He was invalided out of the military service on 26 November 1916 and travelled home to St. Petersburg.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=89}} Mikhail was arrested for a couple of days by the [[Bolsheviks]], but released because of disagreement among the people who detained him.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=94}} The family permanently emigrated from Russia in the midst of the [[Russian Revolution]], which emerged from the social fallback of the World War.<ref name=\"smsport\" /><ref name=\"rustennisfame\" /> First they fled to [[Koreiz]] where they were joined by fugitive [[Felix Yussupov]] who had been freed from his house arrest due to his involvement in the Rasputin murder.<ref name=\"rusart\" /><ref name=\"Rasputin\" /> They agreed to join the [[White Army]], but General [[Anton Denikin]] refused the request because the princes had ties to the Imperial dynasty. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=94}}\nThey sailed to [[Malta]] on 13 April 1919 aboard the British battleship {{HMS|Marlborough|1912|6}}, which also transported several other Russian nobility exiles, including [[Maria Feodorovna (Dagmar of Denmark)|Empress Maria Feodorovna]].<ref name=\"rusart\" />{{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=95}} From there they moved to [[Rome]].{{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=99}} In 1920 he further moved to [[Nice]], where he lived for 17 more years. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=102}}\n\n==Tennis career==\nMikhail Sumarokov-Elston was an eight-time national tennis champion, and also a two-time national indoors champion.<ref name=\"rusart\" /><ref name=\"smsport\" /> He was successful in singles five consecutive times between 1910\u201314, two more time in mixed doubles and also a doubles champion.<ref name=\"smsport\" /> He is still the youngest All-Russia champion to date with his 14 years of age at the time of his first triump. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004a|p=26}} He won his first indoor trophy in 1911 in St. Petersburg. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004a|p=27}}On international level his first main tournament was the 1905 Bad Homburg Cup (of which he won the second-class edition) but lost in the second round to [[Irving Wright]].<ref name=\"spalding\" /> The next year at the [[Wiesbaden]] Championships, where he \u2013 still an adolescent \u2013 was forced to withdraw from the second round after beating Herr von Parpart in the kick-off round.<ref name=\"rusart\" /> He played in several other tournaments throughout Germany, France and Switzerland before returning to Russia.<ref name=\"rusart\" /> There he won city tournaments in Moscow and [[St. Petersburg]].<ref name=\"rustennisfame\" /> Altogether he was crowned two-time St. Petersburg champion in 1912 and 1914 and two-time Moscow champion in 1910 counting the singles and doubles.<ref name=\"rusart\" />\n\nOnly a week after his first St. Petersburg title Sumarokov traveled to [[Sweden]] to participate in the [[1912 Summer Olympics]] with veteran player [[Aleksandr Alenitsyn]]. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=37}} That tournament was also his only preparation for the games as he had to pass his high school diploma exams prior. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=37}} The Olympic draw suffered a setback on expected entries of well-known players due to scheduling conflicts with the [[1912 Wimbledon Championships]]. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=40}} Even Alenitsyn withdrew from the singles outdoor event before its start.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=40}} The first match against the Swedish champion [[Carl Setterwall]] saw an easy two set lead for Sumarokov the third was taken by Sweden after a twenty-game tie and the fourth last set was secured by Russia.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=41}} In the next round [[1912 French Championships]] finalist Oscar Kreuzer waited for his opponent.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=41}} The match, which was witnessed by [[Grand Duchess Maria Pavlovna of Russia (1890\u20131958)|Grand Duchess Maria Pavlovna]] had a back-and-forth fight so fierce that Sumarokov torn the strings of his racquet and had to change it but that could't save him from losing to the German in four sets.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=42}} He found consolation in the doubles tournament where he and Alenitsyn reached the quarterfinals.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=43}}\n\nThe first Russian Championships opened for foreign player registration were held for the first time in 1912.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=43}}  Among the non-Russian entrants were [[Ludwig von Salm-Hoogstraeten]], [[Harold Kitson]] and [[Einer Ulrich]].{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|pp=43-44}} The first of these big tests came in the semifinals against Count Salm. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=44}}The Austrian lost in straight sets only showing resistance in the second. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=44}} The final match should have been a showdown between Kitson and Sumarokov but lasted short.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=45}} After Sumarokov scored the first set 6:3 Kitson got frustrated, complained to the chair umpire, grabbed his towel and left the court citing a right hand injury, which resulted in a walkover home victory.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=45}} He became the undisputed champion after winning the doubles and mixed doubles as well with Count Salm and Ekaterina Hirschfeld respectively. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=46}}\n\n1913 started the same way as the year before, Mikhail had to pass his University exams so he had few chances to practise before setting out to [[Paris]] for the [[World Hard Court Championships]].{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=57}} There he advanced through the first round beating E. Chelli. In the second round he was drawn to face young French prodigy and reigning Olympic champion [[Andr\u00e9 Gobert]].{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=58}} It was a quick defeat as Sumarokov couldn't adapt to the fast-paced net-volley game of Gobert. He was also eliminated from the doubles contest in the very first round mostly due to his partner [[Paul Aym\u00e9]]'s leg injury, which he suffered the previous night and kept them handicapped the whole match. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=60}} Oddly it is thanks to these early exits that he was eligible for the consolation tournament, which was organized for the losers of the first two rounds. There he played his first match against one-half of his recent doubles opponents [[William le Maire de Warz\u00e9e d'Hermalle]] (who had a 6-1 head-to-head record against fellow Belgian Champion [[Paul de Borman]] at the time{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=63}}). {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=60}} This proved to be a tough warm-up for the later matches and it went two sets six-all before Elston broke through. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|pp=61-63}} His former doubles partner [[Paul Aym\u00e9]] resigned from the quarterfinal for unknown reasons and gave him a walkover. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=63}} In the semifinal came a pleasant surprise as the defending consolation title-holder [[Felix Pipes]] lost to him in two fast sets. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=63}} The final was a rematch from the Russian Championships with [[Ludwig von Salm-Hoogstraeten]].{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=63}} The day was struck with extreme heat so intense that it was dangerous to health. After a four set deuce the two finalists agreed to leave the decision to the drawing of lots and finish the match. The luck favored Salm and therefore he was announced the winner. The Cup was awarded to him but as soon as the chairman of the International Lawn Tennis Federation Henry Wallet realized that the winner's name was traditionally engraved onto the cup he reversed his decision and divided the prizes. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=64}}\n\nTwo weeks later Sumarokov was schedules to retain his title at the second annual Russian International Championships. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=66}} It had a star-loaded 136-competitor field with Frenchmen [[Maurice Germot]], [[Max Decugis]] and British [[Arthur Lowe (tennis)|Arthur Lowe]] and [[Charles P. Dixon]] all were present.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=66}} In the first semifinal Sumarokov encountered Germot and overcame him in three straight sets while in the other all-English semifinal Dixon triumphed over Lowe. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=67}} The final showed that the Russian player could stand the ground against world top ten challengers as well. From a two-one set disadvantage he closed the match with a two love-sets and kept his title after 2 hours 54 minutes battle. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|pp=68-69}} He then lost to Dixon in the first round of the doubles but beat him again for the mixed doubles title. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=69}}\n\nAlthough never played in the [[Davis Cup]] he represented Russia in the international matches against Great Britain and France in the last two consecutive years preceding the [[First World War]].<ref name=\"rusart\" /> First in 1913  against the England team of [[Roderick McNair]], [[Albert Prebble]], [[Arthur Lowe (tennis)|Arthur Lowe]] and [[Charles P. Dixon]].{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=70}} The two tennis federation agreed in a 12-match tie with 8 singles and 4 doubles rubbers.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=70}} Sumarokov was still exhausted from his recent Russian Championships final with Dixon and thus lost easily to Lowe and decided to step back from further participation and had to be replaced with inexperienced players.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=71}} As a consequence the Russian team lost. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=72}} This marked the first time that an official national tennis team was formed. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=73}}\n\nIn the 1914 Russian Championships he became a five-time champion after defeating [[Heinrich Kleinschroth]] in a five-set final. Curiosity of the Russian-German meeting was that the [[Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria|Sarajevo regicide]] happened during the tournament (which later escalated into [[World War I]]) and Russia had sent an envoy to France to strengthen a possible alliance against the German Empire.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=80}} Just two weeks later the first Russia-France team match was held. It was agreed to follow [[Davis Cup]] rules and the French delegation was an all-Olympian squad of [[Maurice Germot]], [[Max Decugis]], [[Albert Canet]], [[\u00c9douard M\u00e9ny de Marangue]]{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|pp=83-84}} The team challenge was interrupted in the middle with the outbreak of World War I and the visitors only managed to get onto the last train home before Germany declared war on the [[Russian Empire]] on 19 July.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=85}}\n\nAfter the war he won the Malta Championships in 1919.<ref name=\"rusart\" /> The following year he clinched his first French title at the South of France Championships beating home favorite [[Alain Gerbault]] in a five-set final.<ref name=\"rusart\" /> The next year in [[Nice]] he was eliminated in the semifinal stage by [[Gordon Lowe]].<ref name=\"rusart\" /> However he did defend his South of France title by beating [[Giovanni Balbi de Robecco]] by only dropping two games.<ref name=\"rusart\" /> This was the first time he partnered [[Suzanne Lenglen]] for the mixed contest, which they won.<ref name=\"rusart\" />  In 1922 he was triumphant in Nice] as well, grabbing the singles trophy easily against [[Maurice F\u00e9rrier]].{{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=117}} He took the doubles as well with Gerbault. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=117}}He defended the South of France title for the second time against legendary [[Henri Cochet]] having had beaten [[Charles Aeschlimann]] on his way to the final.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=119}}<ref name=\"PetitNi\u00e7ois\" /> At the same tournament he also repeated his last year feat with Lenglen by overcoming [[Lord Rocksavage]] and [[Elizabeth Ryan]] in the mixed final.<ref name=\"rusart\" /><ref name=\"PetitNi\u00e7ois\" /> He almost celebrated his first triple crown trophy with his teammate Gerbault but fell short in the doubles final against Rocksavage-Cochet.<ref name=\"PetitNi\u00e7ois\" /> It is worth to note that it was the first time Sumarokov played on grass courts. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=124}} In 1923 the team of Sumarokov-Lenglen dropped the same title to [[Randolph Lycett]] and [[Elizabeth Ryan]].<ref name=\"rusart\" /> In 1931 at the Parc Imperial L.T.C. de Nice [[George Lyttleton-Rogers]] and his partner [[Rosie Berthet]] had an overwhelming victory over Sumarokov-Elston and Miss. J. Franks in the mixed final.<ref name=\"tennis&golf\" /> The same year he was also mixed doubles runner-up in two other tournaments at the New Court Lawn Tennis Club and Cannes Lawn Tennis Club losing both times.<ref name=\"rusart\" /> He reached the semifinals of the doubles and mixed in the Nice Tennis Club tournament.<ref name=\"figaro\" /> He won the Russian \u00c9migr\u00e9 Tennis Championships three consecutive times beginning from 1935.<ref name=\"rusart\" /> He turned professional in 1936.<ref name=\"rusart\" />\n\n===Playing style and equipment===\nHe played left-handed with a heavy topspin, after he had to give up his right-handed style due to a childhood injury.<ref name=\"rusart\" />\nHis left-hand serve was so rare that he gave exhibition matches in Germany to [[Grand Duke Alexei Alexandrovich of Russia]] and [[Grand Duke George Mikhailovich of Russia (1863\u20131919)|Grand Duke George Mikhailovich of Russia]].<ref name=\"Straits\" /> According to his contemporary coach Alexandr Stakhovich he was a baseline player with a formidable backhand.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=58}} Sumarokov played with Doherty, [[Slazenger]] and Driva racquets. In 1911 he changed to Maxim racquets. The manufacturer even released an autographed series of racquets with \"Sumarokov\" written on it with golden embossed letters. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004a|p=33}} Later he adjusted his game to putting a curl to the ball as well as hitting it hard and with a high trajectory as described by [[Henri Cochet]] in his book ''Tennis''. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=120}} He is thought to be the first who used this method, which became popular decades later, and being used by many players most notably [[Jimmy Connors]] and [[Guillermo Vilas]].{{sfn|Fomenko|2004c|p=120}}\n\n==Personal life==\nMikhail Sumarokov-Elston was well educated and at the age of thirteen he already spoke five languages.<ref name=\"Straits\" /> Apart from playing tennis he was an amateur [[chess]] player as well. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=76}} He was in a great relationship with Tsar [[Nicholas II of Russia]] and played tennis with a couple of times. {{sfn|Fomenko|2004b|p=49}}In 1913 he was elected an honorary member of the Stade Fran\u00e7ais in Paris.<ref name=\"rusart\" /> He married Natalia Nikolaevna Bellik in 1932.<ref name=\"rusart\" /><ref name=\"findagrave\" /> The next year she gave birth to their daughter Sofia.<ref name=\"rusart\" /> They moved to London in 1937, where led the Anglo-Russian Sports Club in [[Chiswick]].<ref name=\"rusart\" /> Died in the [[University College Hospital]] in 1970 and was buried in the [[Chiswick New Cemetery]].<ref name=\"rusart\" /><ref name=\"findagrave\" /> In 2002 he was inducted to the Russian Tennis Hall of Fame for his sport merits.<ref name=\"rusart\" /><ref name=\"smsport\" />\n\n==Notes==\n*{{note label|birth|a|a}} Sources differ regarding his birth date.{{sfn|Fomenko|2004a|p=15}} However his grave shows  {{OldStyleDate|November 21|1893|9 November}}.<ref name=\"findagrave\" />\n*{{note label|ancestor|b|b}} According to the newest researches the house of Kutuzov is not related to the House of Sumarokov by blood but only by adoption.<ref name=\"Kutuzov\" />\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Count Mikhail Sumarokov-Elston'''\n|2= 2. Count Nikolay Sumarokov-Elston\n|3= 3. Sofia von Koskull\n|4= 4. Count [[Felix Sumarokov-Elston]]\n|5= 5. Countess Elena Sergeievna Sumarokova\n|6= 6. Michael Franzowitsch von Koskull\n|7= 7. Warwara Petrovna Schtscherbatowa\n|8= 8. [[Charles von H\u00fcgel|Karl Alexander Anselm Freiherr von H\u00fcgel]]\n|9= 9. [[Andr\u00e1ssy|countess Jozefa Gr\u00e4fin Andr\u00e1ssy de Cs\u00edkszentkir\u00e1ly et Krasznahorka]]\n|10= 10. Count Sergey Pavlovich Sumarokov\n|11= 11. Marchioness Aleksandra Pavlovna Maruzzi\n|14= 14. Prince Peter Alexandrovich Obolensky\n|15= 15. Princess Ekaterina Andreievna Viasemsky\n|16= 16. Count Johann Aloys Josef H\u00fcgel, later 1st Freiherr von H\u00fcgel\n|17= 17. Countess Anna von Holthof\n|18= 18. Istv\u00e1n Graf Andr\u00e1ssy de Cs\u00edkszentkir\u00e1ly et Krasznahorka\n|19= 19. [[Festetics family|M\u00e1ria Gr\u00e4fin Festetics de Tolna]]\n|20= 20. Pavel Ivanovich Sumarokov\n|21= 21. Princess Maria Vassilevna Galitzina\n|22= 22. Marquis Panos Maruzzi\n|23= 23. Zo\u00eb Ghika\n|28= 28. Prince Alexander Mikhailovich Obolensky\n|29= 29. Anna Mikhailovna Miloslawkya\n|30= 30. Prince Andrei Ivanovich Viazemsky\n|31= 31. Eugenia Kine\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"figaro\">{{cite journal\n| date = 18 January 1931\n| title = Tennis\n| editor = Fran\u00e7ois Coty\n| journal =[[Le Figaro]]\n| location = Paris, France\n| publisher = [[Dassault Group]]\n| page = 8\n| issn = 0182-5852\n| accessdate = 16 June 2013\n| url = http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k296481k/f9.image\n| language = French\n| issue = 18\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"findagrave\">{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/38330825|title=Michael Nikolaevich Soumarokoff-Elston|publisher=[[Find A Grave]]|date=14 June 2009|accessdate=14 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kutuzov\">\u0414\u043e\u043b\u043b\u0438 \u0424\u0438\u043a\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043c\u043e\u043d. \u0414\u043d\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a 1829\u20131837. (in Russian) \u0412\u0435\u0441\u044c \u043f\u0443\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433 / \u041f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u0421. \u041c\u0440\u043e\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439\u2013\u0411\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0448\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u2014 \u041c.: \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0432\u0448\u0435\u0435, 2009. \u2014 1008 \u0441. \u2014 3000 \u044d\u043a\u0437. \u2014 {{ISBN|978-5-902073-66-6}}.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"PetitNi\u00e7ois\">{{cite journal|editor=Albert Lejeune|editor-link=|title=Tennis sur la Cote D'Azur|trans-title=Tennis at the Cote D'Azur|url=http://www.basesdocumentaires-cg06.fr/archives/ImageZoomViewerPA.php?WDIDDOC=2005042935181233241500&WDVOLUMEID=VOL215&j=20&m=03&a=1922&journal=1|volume=43|issue=79|page=2|journal=Le Petit Ni\u00e7ois|date=20 March 1922|publisher=Borriglione|location=[[Nice]], France|language=French|accessdate=11 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"rusart\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rusartnet.com/biographies/russian-sport/tennis/count-mikhail-sumarokov-elston |title=Count Mikhail Sumarokov-Elston \u2013 Tennis \u2013 Russian Sport \u2013 Biographies |publisher=RusArtNet.com |date= |accessdate=13 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304063337/http://www.rusartnet.com/biographies/russian-sport/tennis/count-mikhail-sumarokov-elston |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/su/mikhail-sumarokov-elston-1.html |